    Here are some lessons that i've learned about networking.

    1) Don't just ask for things from people.

    2)Nobody owes me (or you) any of their time.

    3)You can make it more likely that people will give you their time especially on LinkedIn by...
    *Liking, commenting on their posts.
    *Sharing them with your network.
    *Thanking them for any way that they've added value to your life.

    3)I am not a software engineer, they are not a recruiter, and you are not a (whatever you are). We are all just people and people want to feel respected and appreciated.

    4)Provide value before asking for it. If I (or you) don't provide value to others, why should they provide value to me (or you)?

    5)Take the time to learn something about them before messaging them.
    *This allows someone to know that i've actually put effort into communicating with them.

    6)Don't lie and don't be lazy!!!!!

    -There's been so many times where people have reached out to me by saying "I see you have many years of expertise in (whatever area), can you help me get a job"

    Right away I know that they haven't looked at my profile, and are just sending messages to random people just to ask for things.

    Networking can take a lot of effort but it's also simple. Treat others how you would want to be treated and always, always, always value their time.

     hashtag #networking hashtag #softwareengineer hashtag #recruiter

    Positive self talk can make all the difference.

    Earlier today I was thinking "will anyone actually want to hire me"?

    I immediately I answered "of course someone would". Dealing with self doubt can be difficult especially during a career transition but it's important to believe in yourself during these times.

    If you've worked hard and put in 100% then it's important to believe in yourself. Tell yourself "i'm great" or "I can do it". Eventually you'll start to believe it.

    I'm proud of myself for all of my hard work and you should be proud of yourself too.

    Learning a new tech-related skill used to seem like a daunting task.

    I would put in a lot of effort, put a lot of pressure on myself, and then ultimately be disappointed with the result.

    This was the case until I changed a few things.

    Before I would ...

    âŒ "Learn" a lot of concepts at a time, through a video or course, and then apply them at the end.

    âŒ Try to re-create a project that someone else was teaching.

    âŒ Rush so that I could "learn" the concept as fast as possible"

    Now I....

    âœ… Focus on 1 or a few very small concepts within that topic and build a very small project that includes them.

    âœ… Utilize these new concepts to build my own project that I already understand and have built before while utilizing other skills.

    âœ… Take my time and really focus on understanding what i'm learning.

    Just making a few small adjustments really increased my success when it came to learning a new skill.

    The goal is not rush through a new skill that i'm trying to learn, the goal is to actually learn it.
